  <content>
    <title>Python Basics</title>

    <summary>Foundational Python patterns for 3.12+ projects: data structures, control flow, functions, OOP, error handling, file I/O, and tooling (uv, ruff, mypy). Core rule: use built-in generic syntax (list[int], dict[str, int], X | None), prefer uv for all environment and dependency management, and use ruff for both lint and format.</summary>

    <why>
      <p>Legacy patterns (from typing import List, os.path, bare except:, mutable default args) are the most common source of bugs in Python code reviewed by LLMs and generated by agents. Establishing idiomatic 3.12+ patterns at project bootstrap prevents an entire class of regressions and drift.</p>
    </why>

    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Bootstrapping a fresh Python 3.12+ project (pyproject.toml, uv, ruff, mypy, pytest).</item>
        <item>Code review where the issue is fundamentals: mutable defaults, EAFP misuse, legacy typing imports.</item>
        <item>Refactoring legacy 3.7/3.8 code to 3.12+ idioms.</item>
        <item>Generating idiomatic examples or onboarding content.</item>
        <item>Style/idiom gate in CI (ruff UP, B, E, F rule sets).</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>

    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Inside a domain-specific feature (Django model, FastAPI route) — load the domain methodology; this overview is too generic.</item>
        <item>Performance optimization — route to python-modern-2026/ or specialized profiling tooling.</item>
        <item>Type-system depth (generics, ParamSpec, Protocol) — route to python-typing/.</item>
        <item>Async patterns — route to python-async/.</item>
        <item>Testing strategies — route to a pytest methodology.</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>

    <section name="data-structures">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Use built-in generic syntax for type hints: list[int], dict[str, int], set[str], tuple[int, ...] — never from typing import List, Dict, Set, Tuple.</statement>
        <rationale>Built-in generics (PEP 585, Python 3.9+) are the current standard. The typing module aliases were deprecated in 3.9 and should trigger ruff UP006/UP035 warnings. Removing them reduces import noise.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Use X | Y union syntax instead of Union[X, Y] and X | None instead of Optional[X] — requires Python 3.10+ or from __future__ import annotations.</statement>
        <rationale>PEP 604 pipe union reads as "or" and is shorter. Optional[X] obscures intent; X | None is explicit about nullability. ruff UP007 auto-upgrades on --fix.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Use tuple for fixed-arity heterogeneous sequences and dict keys; use list for variable-length homogeneous sequences.</statement>
        <rationale>Tuple immutability makes it hashable (usable as dict key) and communicates fixed structure. Lists communicate mutability and variable length. Mixing the two semantics confuses readers.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Use set for membership tests and deduplication; use frozenset when the set must be hashable or passed to functions as a contract.</statement>
        <rationale>set lookup is O(1) vs O(n) for list. frozenset is the immutable counterpart, suitable as dict key or function argument when mutation must be prevented.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Prefer collections.defaultdict over dict.setdefault() for grouped accumulation; prefer collections.Counter over manual frequency counting.</statement>
        <rationale>defaultdict eliminates the "check-then-insert" pattern in loop bodies. Counter is purpose-built for frequency tallies and exposes .most_common() without sorting manually.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <example type="good" title="Idiomatic grouping with defaultdict and counting with Counter">
        <code lang="python"><![CDATA[
from collections import defaultdict, Counter

def group_by_status(orders: list[dict]) -> dict[str, list[dict]]:
    grouped: defaultdict[str, list[dict]] = defaultdict(list)
    for order in orders:
        grouped[order["status"]].append(order)
    return dict(grouped)

def top_words(text: str, n: int = 10) -> list[tuple[str, int]]:
    counts = Counter(text.lower().split())
    return counts.most_common(n)
]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="comprehensions">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Use list/dict/set comprehensions for single-expression transforms; use a for-loop when the body contains side effects, early returns, or complex logic.</statement>
        <rationale>Comprehensions signal "transform a collection" — the intent is clear at a glance. Comprehensions with if/else branches, nested calls, or appended side effects become harder to read than a for-loop with a comment.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Use generator expressions ((x for x in ...)) instead of list comprehensions when the result is consumed once (passed to sum(), any(), max(), etc.).</statement>
        <rationale>Generator expressions are lazy — they avoid materializing an intermediate list in memory. sum(x*x for x in data) is both shorter and more memory-efficient than sum([x*x for x in data]).</rationale>
      </rule>

      <example type="good" title="Comprehension vs generator vs loop — correct choice per use case">
        <code lang="python"><![CDATA[
# List comprehension — result is iterated multiple times
active_ids: list[int] = [u["id"] for u in users if u["active"]]

# Generator expression — consumed once by sum
total = sum(item["price"] * item["qty"] for item in cart)

# Dict comprehension — invert a mapping
id_to_name: dict[int, str] = {u["id"]: u["name"] for u in users}

# For-loop with side effect — comprehension would be wrong here
for user in users:
    if user["active"]:
        send_notification(user["email"])  # Side effect: don't use comprehension
]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="pattern-matching">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Use match/case (Python 3.10+) for dispatch on structure, not just value equality. Use case _: exhaustive fallthrough instead of a final bare else.</statement>
        <rationale>Pattern matching deconstructs data (sequences, mappings, classes) directly in the case clause. case _: is the structural equivalent of else: but scales to multiple pattern arms without nested if/elif chains.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <example type="good" title="Structural pattern matching on a command tuple">
        <code lang="python"><![CDATA[
def handle_command(command: list[str]) -> None:
    match command:
        case ["quit"]:
            raise SystemExit
        case ["load", filename]:
            load_file(filename)
        case ["save", filename, *options]:
            save_file(filename, options)
        case ["go", direction] if direction in {"north", "south", "east", "west"}:
            move(direction)
        case _:
            raise ValueError(f"Unknown command: {command!r}")
]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="functions-and-classes">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Annotate all public function signatures with type hints including the return type. Use -> None for procedures that have no return value.</statement>
        <rationale>Without return-type annotations, mypy skips the function body in its inferred-return analysis. Explicit annotations make the contract clear and improve LLM code generation accuracy.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Never use mutable objects as default argument values. Use None as the default and initialize inside the body.</statement>
        <rationale>Default argument values are evaluated once at function definition time, not per call. A mutable default like def f(items=[]) shares the same list across all calls — a classic Python footgun.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Use keyword-only arguments (def f(*, name: str)) for clarity when a function has more than two positional parameters or when argument names carry intent.</statement>
        <rationale>Keyword-only arguments prevent positional ordering mistakes at call sites. They also make function signatures self-documenting and resistant to refactoring breaks when argument order changes.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <example type="bad" title="Mutable default argument — the classic Python bug">
        <code lang="python"><![CDATA[
def add_tag(tag: str, tags: list[str] = []) -> list[str]:  # Bug: shared list!
    tags.append(tag)
    return tags
]]></code>
      </example>

      <example type="good" title="Correct: None default, keyword-only, type hints">
        <code lang="python"><![CDATA[
def add_tag(tag: str, *, tags: list[str] | None = None) -> list[str]:
    result = tags if tags is not None else []
    result.append(tag)
    return result
]]></code>
      </example>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Always apply @functools.wraps(func) in decorator wrappers to preserve the wrapped function's __name__, __doc__, and signature.</statement>
        <rationale>Without functools.wraps, introspection tools (help(), Sphinx, FastAPI's OpenAPI) see the wrapper's metadata instead of the original function's. This breaks auto-generated docs and tracebacks.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <example type="good" title="Decorator preserving wrapped function metadata">
        <code lang="python"><![CDATA[
import functools
from collections.abc import Callable
from typing import Any

def log_call[**P, R](func: Callable[P, R]) -> Callable[P, R]:
    @functools.wraps(func)
    def wrapper(*args: P.args, **kwargs: P.kwargs) -> R:
        result = func(*args, **kwargs)
        return result
    return wrapper
]]></code>
      </example>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Use @dataclass for data containers with typed fields instead of bare __init__ methods or named tuples with many fields.</statement>
        <rationale>Dataclasses auto-generate __init__, __repr__, and __eq__ from field declarations. @dataclass(frozen=True) produces an immutable, hashable value object without manual __hash__.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Use field(default_factory=list) for mutable defaults in dataclasses — never assign [] or {} directly as a field default.</statement>
        <rationale>Dataclass field defaults are shared the same way function argument defaults are. The default_factory creates a fresh instance per object. A bare [] default raises ValueError at class definition time in modern Python.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <example type="good" title="Dataclass with mutable field and frozen variant">
        <code lang="python"><![CDATA[
from dataclasses import dataclass, field
from typing import ClassVar

@dataclass
class ShoppingCart:
    user_id: int
    items: list[str] = field(default_factory=list)
    _total_carts: ClassVar[int] = 0  # Class variable, not an instance field

    def add(self, item: str) -> None:
        self.items.append(item)

@dataclass(frozen=True)
class Point:
    x: float
    y: float

    def distance_to(self, other: "Point") -> float:
        return ((self.x - other.x) ** 2 + (self.y - other.y) ** 2) ** 0.5
]]></code>
      </example>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Use Protocol for structural duck-typing contracts between modules instead of ABC inheritance. Add @runtime_checkable only when isinstance() checks at runtime are actually needed.</statement>
        <rationale>Protocol satisfies the Open/Closed principle: a class satisfies a Protocol without importing it. ABC requires explicit inheritance, creating import coupling. @runtime_checkable adds per-call overhead — omit it for hot paths.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="error-handling">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Prefer EAFP (Easier to Ask Forgiveness than Permission) over LBYL (Look Before You Leap) for operations where the failure path is genuinely exceptional.</statement>
        <rationale>EAFP eliminates race conditions in the LBYL check-then-act window. In a concurrent system, a "key in dict" check before "dict[key]" can fail between the two steps. EAFP also avoids double-lookup in hash tables.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <example type="bad" title="LBYL: double lookup, race-prone">
        <code lang="python"><![CDATA[
# LBYL — double lookup, possible TOCTOU race
if "user_id" in request.data:
    user_id = request.data["user_id"]
    if user_id in user_cache:
        user = user_cache[user_id]
    else:
        user = None
]]></code>
      </example>

      <example type="good" title="EAFP: single lookup, explicit about failure">
        <code lang="python"><![CDATA[
# EAFP — single lookup, clear intent
try:
    user_id = request.data["user_id"]
    user = user_cache[user_id]
except KeyError:
    user = None

# Alternatively for simple None defaults:
user_id = request.data.get("user_id")
user = user_cache.get(user_id) if user_id else None
]]></code>
      </example>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Keep try blocks as narrow as possible — wrap only the exact operation that can raise the expected exception, not the surrounding logic.</statement>
        <rationale>A wide try block silently catches unexpected exceptions from unrelated code. If process(data) raises ValueError for a different reason than int(data["value"]), the except clause hides the bug.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Never use bare except: or except Exception: without re-raising or logging the exception with its full traceback.</statement>
        <rationale>Bare except swallows SystemExit, KeyboardInterrupt, and GeneratorExit. Bare except Exception swallows programming errors that should crash loudly. Silent swallowing produces impossible-to-debug state.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <example type="bad" title="Wide try block — hides unrelated bugs">
        <code lang="python"><![CDATA[
try:
    user_id = int(request.data["user_id"])
    user = User.objects.get(id=user_id)
    send_welcome_email(user)  # Bug here silently swallowed!
except (ValueError, KeyError, User.DoesNotExist):
    return Response({"error": "invalid"}, status=400)
]]></code>
      </example>

      <example type="good" title="Narrow try blocks — each exception source is isolated">
        <code lang="python"><![CDATA[
try:
    user_id = int(request.data["user_id"])
except (ValueError, KeyError):
    return Response({"error": "user_id must be an integer"}, status=400)

try:
    user = User.objects.get(id=user_id)
except User.DoesNotExist:
    return Response({"error": "user not found"}, status=404)

send_welcome_email(user)  # Allowed to raise freely — bug visibility preserved
]]></code>
      </example>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Define a base exception class per module or app (e.g., class OrderError(Exception): ...), then subclass for each specific error. Never raise bare Exception from library or service code.</statement>
        <rationale>A base exception per domain allows callers to catch all domain errors with one clause while still distinguishing specific cases. Bare Exception cannot be caught selectively without catching everything.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <example type="good" title="Domain exception hierarchy with typed context">
        <code lang="python"><![CDATA[
class OrderError(Exception):
    """Base for all order domain errors."""

class OrderNotFound(OrderError):
    def __init__(self, order_id: int) -> None:
        self.order_id = order_id
        super().__init__(f"Order {order_id} not found")

class InsufficientStock(OrderError):
    def __init__(self, product_id: int, requested: int, available: int) -> None:
        self.product_id = product_id
        self.requested = requested
        self.available = available
        super().__init__(
            f"Product {product_id}: requested {requested}, available {available}"
        )

# Caller can catch broadly or specifically
try:
    process_order(order_id)
except InsufficientStock as e:
    notify_reorder(e.product_id)
except OrderError as e:
    logger.warning("Order error: %s", e)
]]></code>
      </example>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Use dict.get(key, default) when a missing key is a normal expected case with a simple default. Use try/except KeyError when missing means an error condition that needs explicit handling.</statement>
        <rationale>dict.get() is idiomatic for optional lookup with defaults. try/except KeyError signals that absence is unexpected and requires different behavior — not just a fallback value. Mixing them leads to inconsistent error semantics.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="modern-tooling">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Use uv as the single tool for Python version management, virtual environments, and package installation. Do not use pip, venv, or pyenv alongside uv in new projects.</statement>
        <rationale>uv is 10-100x faster than pip (warm cache), manages Python versions itself (uv python install), and uses a global cache to avoid redundant downloads. One tool eliminates the pip/pip-tools/pyenv/virtualenv coordination complexity.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Pin the Python version per project with a .python-version file (uv python pin 3.12). Keep it in sync with requires-python in pyproject.toml.</statement>
        <rationale>Without a pinned version, uv sync picks the highest available Python. Team members on different minor versions encounter subtle behavior differences (stdlib additions, syntax changes). .python-version + requires-python provide two layers of enforcement.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <example type="good" title="uv project bootstrap and common commands">
        <code lang="bash"><![CDATA[
# Bootstrap
uv init my_project --python 3.12
cd my_project
uv python pin 3.12

# Add dependencies
uv add fastapi pydantic
uv add --dev pytest ruff mypy pytest-cov

# Run in virtualenv without activating
uv run python main.py
uv run pytest
uv run ruff check . --fix

# Sync lockfile (CI or new clone)
uv sync
]]></code>
      </example>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Consolidate all project config in pyproject.toml: project metadata, build system (hatchling), ruff, mypy, and pytest settings. Do not use setup.cfg, setup.py, .flake8, or mypy.ini.</statement>
        <rationale>Multiple config files fragment project setup. pyproject.toml is the PEP 517/518 standard and all major tools (ruff, mypy, pytest, hatchling, uv) support it. Consolidation reduces cognitive overhead when onboarding.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Use ruff for both linting and formatting (ruff check + ruff format). Enable rule groups: E (errors), F (pyflakes), I (isort), B (bugbear), UP (pyupgrade), C4 (comprehensions), T20 (no-print).</statement>
        <rationale>Ruff replaces Flake8 + Black + isort + pyupgrade in a single binary that runs in milliseconds. Rule group UP auto-upgrades deprecated typing syntax to modern equivalents. T20 blocks accidental print() in production code.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Run ruff check . --fix before committing to auto-fix all safe-fixable violations. Set ruff format . in pre-commit hooks to enforce consistent formatting.</statement>
        <rationale>Auto-fix eliminates manual correction of mechanical style issues. Pre-commit hooks make formatting non-negotiable — no "I forgot" in code review. CI runs ruff check without --fix to catch unfixable violations.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Run mypy with strict = true in CI. For new projects, start strict from day one. For legacy codebases, enable strict incrementally per module using [[tool.mypy.overrides]].</statement>
        <rationale>Strict mode enables disallow_untyped_defs, warn_return_any, and no_implicit_optional — the most impactful flags. Adding strict to an existing codebase all at once generates hundreds of errors; per-module overrides let you clean up incrementally.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Exclude migrations/ and tests/ from strict mode via mypy overrides. Tests use dynamic fixtures; migrations are generated code — both produce false positives under strict.</statement>
        <rationale>Django migrations use dynamic field references that mypy cannot resolve without django-stubs. Test files use pytest.fixture and conftest patterns that produce untyped-def noise. Excluding them focuses strict mode on production code.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <templates>
      <template path="templates/pyproject.toml" purpose="Modern pyproject.toml with ruff (line-length 100), mypy strict, pytest config."/>
      <template path="templates/bootstrap.sh" purpose="One-shot project bootstrap: uv init, dev deps, ruff/mypy/pytest config."/>
    </templates>

